    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1917067181" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1917067181" />
    <a title="Angus Mcfarlane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5885099-angus-mcfarlane"><img alt="Angus Mcfarlane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1373228842p2/5885099.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1917067181?book_show_action=true">Apr 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angus Mcfarlane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angus Mcfarlane" href="/user/show/5885099-angus-mcfarlane">Angus Mcfarlane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780749953089" href="/book/show/11281104-mindfulness">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5885099-angus-mcfarlane?shelf=business">business</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5885099-angus-mcfarlane?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5885099-angus-mcfarlane?shelf=spirituality">spirituality</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1917067181" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2877078253687808458">I was introduced to mindfulness by stealth on a work leadership course, and reacted defensively. I have always gone into such courses hesitantly and the introduction of an ostensibly Buddhist/yoga exercise on the basis of the facilitator claiming &apos;the evidence is in&apos; to a bunch of scientists added to my reserve. I managed the course my own way, and tried to obtain some of the apparent evidence to find out for myself. It was ok, but didn&apos;t convince me to begin mindfulness.<br/><br/>Four months into the str</span>
  <span id="freeText2877078253687808458" style="display:none">I was introduced to mindfulness by stealth on a work leadership course, and reacted defensively. I have always gone into such courses hesitantly and the introduction of an ostensibly Buddhist/yoga exercise on the basis of the facilitator claiming 'the evidence is in' to a bunch of scientists added to my reserve. I managed the course my own way, and tried to obtain some of the apparent evidence to find out for myself. It was ok, but didn't convince me to begin mindfulness.<br /><br />Four months into the stress of an overseas, foreign language work assignment I saw this book at the airport on my first trip home and thought it might perhaps be worth a further look. So, eight weeks later my life is changed just as the book said it would. Well, sort of. Life always changes so I'm being a little cynical. I was open to the experience, and I think it did have a helpful effect, but I also don't think it was as life changing as it claimed.<br /><br />Beginning with the positive, the discipline of stopping to reflect and still the heart and mind was good. My work schedule has become increasingly challenging, without likelihood of relief if I allow it to be dictated by 'demand'. Taking stock and going to the new day, or the afternoon, refreshed or at least prepared, was good. It was also useful to learn more about how to pause during an intense conversation (not the books subject, by the way) by being present was good. The book suggests many interesting exercises aside from the meditations that are good for reconnecting with life, the chocolate meditation and the mindful walk being two I particularly enjoyed.<br /><br />Unfortunately, I felt the process lost momentum about half way through. Also, some of the meditations seemed to lack impact, the sounds one distracted by the sound of the teachers voice, whilst the body scan was too relaxing - I don't think there was one I could stay awake for all the way through. As the program progressed, the increasing pressure of work coincided with the increased time commitment to the meditations, causing its own stress. <br /><br />As far as the Buddhism line runs, the book itself has no religious content, so it shouldn't necessarily be regarded as religion by stealth. On the other hand most of the extra reading was related to Buddhist practice, so....hmm. I'm not in a position to comment other than from a Christian perspective. I'm sure there are Christian traditions that line up nicely with mindfulness, monasticism and 'celebration of discipline' come to mind, albeit with a theological focus rather than a body centric one. I am still exploring this relationship (mindfulness vs Christian faith) but I have concluded that it need not be antagonistic.<br /><br />Mindfulness is not for everyone. Nor is this book. But going from a book and learning about this your own way (I suspect there are plenty of sources to learn from, not all reliable) at least allowed me to form an independent opinion. I think it has benefited me, so I would encourage others to give it a go. But adapt it to the tradition you come at it from. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2877078253687808458" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

