    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2287788714" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2287788714" />
    <a title="Alexander Johnson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/66416118-alexander-johnson"><img alt="Alexander Johnson" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2287788714?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alexander Johnson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alexander Johnson" href="/user/show/66416118-alexander-johnson">Alexander Johnson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2287788714" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18116507372060636254">Bottom line this is a book about meditating. <br/>A lost art in the Western world, I have always appreciated the Eastern emphasis on this practice and the obvious health advantages it has on those cultures. However, it will take a paradigm shift for the typical “American” reader to really benefit from what “Frantic World” promotes. <br/>I&apos;m not going to sugarcoat this and say that it&apos;s easy to find the time to meditate. It&apos;s not. We have to work hard to make sure that they find time day that we need make </span>
  <span id="freeText18116507372060636254" style="display:none">Bottom line this is a book about meditating. <br />A lost art in the Western world, I have always appreciated the Eastern emphasis on this practice and the obvious health advantages it has on those cultures. However, it will take a paradigm shift for the typical “American” reader to really benefit from what “Frantic World” promotes. <br />I'm not going to sugarcoat this and say that it's easy to find the time to meditate. It's not. We have to work hard to make sure that they find time day that we need make it happen. That's not easy with work, family, and life. However, it is worth the time that you put in. I've included it in my daily life - passively as well as actively - meditating for short periods of the day has helped me and I have every reason to believe it will help you. <br />I heartily recommend this book and others like it that attempt to re-engineer our minds to become our friend and not our enemy. <br />Speaking about reading, here's a list of a couple of other books that I have found helpful in this process. They more emphasize the practice of mindfulness in everyday life, rather than purposeful meditation. Hopefully anyone who is reading this will find them helpful as well:<br />•	 “Eat Stop Eat”  <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://tinyurl.com/ycs8g7oo">https://tinyurl.com/ycs8g7oo</a>  <br />This book is a really good program for anyone who is trying to gain mind power over weight problems.<br />•	 “Mindfulness: An Eight Week Plan for Finding Peace in a Frantic World <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://amzn.to/2GWEMhp">http://amzn.to/2GWEMhp</a>  <br />This book. . . be sure to check out the options for Kindle and used hard cover prices that are quite reasonable. <br />•	 “Manifestation Miracle”  <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://tinyurl.com/yb87az3u">https://tinyurl.com/yb87az3u</a>  <br />More of a New Age approach to bringing life changes your way. I like the positive approach though, it is a little top heavy on name-it-claim it mentality. <br />Back to the book, here's a few random thoughts on what I have learned throughout the book:<br />1. Don't label yourself as having things, being a particular type person, or being prone to this condition or that condition. We're all people and we all have emotions. The people that you see in life have similar feelings that you and I have. There's nothing wrong with you if you hive difficult emotions from time to time. Everyone does. Your most stalwart examples are dealing with heavy burdens they are perhaps just using coping strategies you might learn from being mindful. <br />2. The key is not to avoid having negative emotions, it's to not let them control you. Recognize that a thought is just a thought. It can't hurt you, unless you do something that empowers it, like excesses or addictions to avoid it. Trying to avoid anything just makes it worse. When you face your fears you can master them. Mindfulness helps tremendously with this one.<br /><br />3. Always try to have as many positive thoughts as possible and to look at things in the most favorable light. Hope springs from thinking of positive outcomes. Always have hope, speak to that and while negative things happen, they can’t take your soul. <br />4. Faith and religion are not for the weak and hopeless they are foundations for sound thinking by facing fears with a hope for a future and with an expectation that there is more than this momentary pain. <br />So there’s a few thoughts about mindfulness and hopes that you benefit from the message as much as I do.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18116507372060636254" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


